The baby was diagnosed with spina bifida and would not survive if removed from his mother's womb. Little Samuel's mother, Julie Armas, is an obstetrics nurse in Atlanta. She knew of Dr. Bruner's remarkable surgical procedure. Practicing at Vanderbilt University Medical Center in Nashville, he performs these special operations while the baby is still in the womb.

During the procedure, the doctor removes the uterus via C-section and makes a small incision to operate on the baby. As Dr. Bruner completed the surgery on Samuel, the little guy reached his tiny, but fully developed hand through the incision and firmly grasped the surgeon's finger. Dr. Bruner was reported as saying that when his finger was grasped, it was the most emotional moment of his life, and that for an instant during the procedure he was just frozen, totally immobile.

The photograph captures this amazing event with perfect clarity. The editors titled the picture, "Hand of Hope." The text explaining the picture begins, "The tiny hand of 21-week-old fetus Samuel Alexander Armas emerges from the mother's uterus to grasp the finger of Dr. Joseph Bruner as if thanking the doctor for the gift of life."

Little Samuel's mother said they "wept for days" when they saw the picture. She said, "The photo reminds us pregnancy isn't about disability or an illness, it's about a little person" Samuel was born in perfect health, the operation 100 percent successful. Before we had government healthcare and all the bureaucracy that followed with it, how did the poor obtain healthcare in the United States? It was provided by charities, by churches, by friends and family members. Doctors would care for them for free, pro-bono. No one allowed anyone to suffer needlessly. There were many religious doctors and people with a soul, with a conscience, that even devoted their lives to care for the poor and not for monetary gain. And the cost of healthcare and insurance back then was a fraction of what it is now. The reason why education and healthcare is so expensive in this country is because of unintended consequences from decisions made with the very best of intentions. I'll try to give a short and practical explanation. If the easy and free credit for student loans dried out today, and no one could take out a loan to attend a good college, you would see empty colleges. And colleges then would either be forced to go out of business, or lower their costs and expenses. Today you see colleges adding building to building, facility after facility, like a nuclear arms race, to attract students and their extremely hefty loans that make them a tremendous profit. All of this unnecessary waste and spending would be eliminated, and education would again be affordable. But even online schools with a fraction of the operating cost of a brick and mortar school charge almost the same amount. And why? Because they can, and who wouldn't if they were in their position, if the people are willing to take out an enormous loan and pay for it.

Berniecare is essentially a monopsony: a single buyer environment that results in lower prices. In this case, the only buyer is the government. Of course this will lower healthcare costs for people. Alright so I don't know if anyone is interested, but this whole idea that women are payed less because of gender discrimination like Hilary and many others say is nonsense. Its the about the choices an individual makes. The 77% that everyone wants you to believe is the gender pay gap is false since they are taking the median from all full time jobs in the country. That is like comparing a male engineers' salary to a female elementary school teachers' salary. There has been research done (Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis) that shows that women earn about 95% of what a man earns for the same job. The other 5% wage gap is caused by two factors. The first is that women are much less likely to negotiate their salaries compared to their male counterparts (There are numerous experiments published that show this, you can find them on the internet). The second is that women are more often than not the primary nurturers of a families children. They are not able to fully commit to their work whereas men can do so more often.
That leaves leaves only a slim possibility that women have lower wages due to gender discrimination.

"The GOP-authored bill was crafted as a response to a proposal from ex-Commodity Futures Trading Commission Chair Brooksley Born to ramp up oversight of derivatives. But the version Sanders initially voted for was more benign than the final, Gramm-authored version, and it didn't draw any of the protests that the 1999 repeal of Glass-Steagall did. In October 2000, the bill passed the House by a vote of 377 to 4 (51 members didn't vote), and then sat on the shelf for weeks.

But in December, Gramm -- after¬†coordinating¬†with top Clinton administration officials -- added much harder-edged deregulatory language to the bill, then attached the entire package to a must-pass 11,000-page bill funding the entire federal government. After Gramm's workshopping, the legislation included new language saying the federal government "shall not exercise regulatory authority with respect to, a covered swap agreement offered, entered into, or provided by a bank." That ended all government oversight of derivatives purchased or traded by banks. He also created the so-called "Enron Loophole," which barred federal oversight of energy trading on electronic platforms.

Sanders has since hammered the CFMA, its architects and specific provisions in Senate hearings and on the Senate floor. He helped push through legislation to close the Enron loophole in 2008.
